    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Colombian Violence</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Charles H Roberts letter urges US to halt sale of war-related materiel to Colombia in light of its poor record on upholding human rights and fighting drug trade (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Colombia's Spectrum of Sorrows'' (editorial, Jan. 3) notes that ''political violence now kills more than 10 Colombians a day.'' In fact, another 60 people are killed every day in violence not classified as political, though the motives are often unknown.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Colombia's Spectrum of Sorrows'' (editorial, Jan. 3) notes that ''political violence now kills more than 10 Colombians a day.'' In fact, another 60 people are killed every day in violence not classified as political, though the motives are often unknown.</p>
        <p>You urge Washington to press the military ''to respect civilian orders to arrest paramilitary death squads.'' But this alone would not be sufficient. Official Colombian documents brought to light by human rights organizations last year suggest ties between the paramilitary squads and the Government's military intelligence networks. State use of paramilitaries needs to be ended.</p>
        <p>In view of the consistently poor human rights record of the Colombian Government and the ineffectiveness of Washington's war on drugs, the Clinton Administration should suspend all war-related materiel to Colombia.</p>
        <p>CHARLES H. ROBERTS  Washington, Jan. 8, 1998</p>
      </block>
